[3] Norovirus, suspected, cruise ship - USA (Caribbean ex Philadelphia)
Date: Sun 2 May 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: The Australian, Sat 1 May 2004 [edited]
<http://www.theaustralian.news.com.au/common/story_page/0,5744,9439503%255E1702,00.html>


USA: norovirus outbreak affects passengers on Caribbean cruise
-----------------------------------------------
Passengers on a Norwegian Cruise Lines ship that left Bermuda today
[Sat 1 May 2004] said their Caribbean journey was fraught with
problems, including a stomach bug that left more than 30 people sick,
power outages, and an overpowering fuel smell. The company flew 39 of
the cruise liner's 1111 passengers home after paying for their hotel
stays last night [Fri 30 Apr 2004].

The Norwegian Crown is due back in Philadelphia, in the USA, on Sun 2
May 2004. Norwegian Cruise Lines spokeswoman Susan Robison said tests
had determined that the stomach bug the passengers had contracted was
not linked to food. She said that the crew was taking steps to
disinfect the ship to eliminate the virus. Passengers were also angry
about soot in a hot tub and pool, as well as afternoon power outages
on 2 days that affected elevators, lights, toilets, and water.

In 2003, 55 passengers and 5 crew members on a 7-day Norwegian cruise
to Alaska contracted what appeared to be norovirus infection, a virus
that has caused thousands of cruise ship passengers to fall ill. The
illnesses occurred on the Miami-based Norwegian Cruise Lines vessel
Norwegian Sky.

Noroviruses -- which include Norwalk virus and related viruses -- can
cause diarrhea, stomach pain and vomiting for 24 to 48 hours. They
are spread through food, water and close contact with infected people
or with things that they have touched.

[Byline: Matthew Taylor]

[The term norovirus is the collective name for enteric viruses
belonging to the genus _Norovirus_ of the family _Caliciviridae_. The
type species of the genus is _Norwalk virus_ from which the name
norovirus is derived. Norwalk is a town in Ohio where the virus was
1st isolated. Viruses in this genus are associated with epidemic
gastroenteritis in humans, and, previously, were designated according
to their appearance by negative-stain electron microscopy as "small
round structured viruses." - Mod.CP]

