[4] Norovirus, suspected, location undisclosed - USA (Fairbanks, Alaska)
Date: Sun 2 May 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Fairbanks Daily News, Sat 1 May 2004 [edited]
<http://www.news-miner.com/Stories/0,1413,113~7244~2122879,00.html>


USA: suspected norovirus outbreak affects 18 people in Fairbanks (Alaska)
-----------------------------------------------
Public health workers are investigating a small outbreak in Fairbanks
of highly contagious norovirus infection. 18 people have fallen ill
with norovirus-like symptoms, which are diarrhea, nausea, and
vomiting, according to Marc Chimonas, a physician with the Alaska
Division of Public Health, who traveled here from Anchorage in
response to the outbreak. 2 public places believed to have been
contaminated with the virus have been disinfected, Chimonas said. The
doctor refused to name them, citing the potential for stigma.
"Publicly pointing fingers at these 2 places is not going to prevent
spread of the disease," Chimonas said.

5 of the 18 norovirus cases are extremely mild, Chimonas said.
Norovirus is the [collective name for members of the former genus
_Norwalk-like viruses_, now designated by the genus name
_Norovirus_]. Noroviruses are spread person-to-person, typically by
eating food or by drinking water contaminated by the feces of an
infected person, according to a public health fact sheet. [Norovirus
infection] is not deadly, but people who have it "have a distinct
feeling that they've been poisoned," one physician said. The symptoms
typically last about 2 days.

Chimonas is working with local public health workers and officials
with the Alaska Department of Environmental Conservation to
distribute information about how to prevent the spread of the virus.
"Hand-washing is key," Chimonas said. "Everyone in town needs to be
very vigilant about hand-washing. Since this is very contagious, we
don't want the outbreak to get any bigger. It can be disruptive for
the economy if a lot of people get sick." Chimonas has not tracked
down the source of the virus, and it is unclear whether he will
succeed.

The virus commonly makes its way to Alaska via cruise ships. The
virus has not yet been confirmed through laboratory testing -- final
confirmation is due on Wed 5 May 2004 -- but the symptoms point
almost beyond doubt to norovirus, Chimonas said.

Fairbanks Memorial Hospital is accepting stool samples from residents
with norovirus-like symptoms who want to confirm whether they are
infected, Bullock said. Cups for the samples are available in the
emergency room. Residents suffering from diarrhea, nausea and
vomiting should take care to remain hydrated, Chimonas and Bullock
said.

[Byline: Amanda Bohman]

